:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"How To Hide Events From Unregistered Users\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"http://tri.be/how-to-hide-events-from-unregistered-users/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"http://tri.be/how-to-hide-events-from-unregistered-users/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 02 Jul 2013 22:00:23 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Tutorial\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:22:\"http://tri.be/?p=49892\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:584:\"DISCLAIMER: WordPress allows data to be queried in many and varied forms and other plugins/themes may be active on your site which do not &#8220;play by the rules&#8221; &#8211; so please be aware that, although this should be a functional solution in most cases, it does not cover every possible eventuality. It may be that you wish to &#8220;lock down&#8221; your event and calendar data to authenticated users only. Currently there is no easy way &#8230; <a href=\"http://tri.be/how-to-hide-events-from-unregistered-users/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Barry\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2023:\"<p><em>DISCLAIMER: WordPress allows data to be queried in many and varied forms and other plugins/themes may be active on your site which do not &#8220;play by the rules&#8221; &#8211; so please be aware that, although this should be a functional solution in most cases, it does not cover every possible eventuality.<br />\n</em></p>\n<p>It may be that you wish to &#8220;lock down&#8221; your event and calendar data to authenticated users only. Currently there is no easy way to do this out of the box, however by adding the following chunk of code to your themes functions.php file you can effectively stop unauthenticated users from viewing events.</p>\n<pre class=\"brush: php; title: ; notranslate\">\r\n// Let\'s restrict events to logged in users only\r\nadd_filter(\'pre_get_posts\', \'restrict_events\', 100);\r\n\r\nfunction restrict_events($query) {\r\n	// Do nothing if the current user is logged in\r\n	$user = wp_get_current_user();\r\n	if (isset($user-&gt;ID) and $user-&gt;ID &gt; 0) return;\r\n\r\n	// We are only interested in event queries\r\n	if (!isset($query-&gt;query_vars[\'post_type\']) or $query-&gt;query_vars[\'post_type\'] !== TribeEvents::POSTTYPE) return;\r\n\r\n	// Remove the results\r\n	add_filter(\'the_posts\', \'wipeout_posts\', 100);\r\n}\r\n\r\nfunction wipeout_posts($posts) {\r\n	// Tidy up first of all\r\n	remove_filter(\'the_posts\', \'wipeout_posts\', 100);\r\n\r\n	// Return an empty array - but we could iterate through and be selective about what is removed,\r\n	// or inject a stub post or even redirect to a &quot;Sorry you must be logged in&quot; page\r\n	return array();\r\n}\r\n</pre>\n<p>This approach could also be easily extended. For example, by tweaking<em>wipeout_posts()</em> certain events (perhaps tagged or categorized as <em>public)</em> could remain available even to unauthenticated users, or the user could be redirected to a page explaining that they need to log in (and register) first of all &#8230; or both of those &#8230; however we&#8217;ll leave more advanced stuff like that to you guys and your imaginations  </p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:62:\"http://tri.be/how-to-hide-events-from-unregistered-users/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:49:\"Querying ongoing and single day events separately\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:64:\"http://tri.be/querying-ongoing-and-single-day-events-separately/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:73:\"http://tri.be/querying-ongoing-and-single-day-events-separately/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 02 Jul 2013 21:54:58 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s